        <h1><i class="fas fa-clock"></i> Time Dilation and Mass Density</h1>
        <p>
            Time dilation, a key concept in relativity, occurs when the passage of time slows down for an object 
            moving at high speeds or in a strong gravitational field. The Unified Universe Theory extends this 
            concept by suggesting that mass density also plays a significant role in time dilation.
        </p>
        <p>
            The extended time dilation equation is:
        </p>
        <div class="math-equation">
            <span>Δt' = Δt * √(1 - v² / c²) * (1 / (1 + G * m * ρ / c²))</span>
        </div>
        <p>
            In this equation, <strong>Δt'</strong> is the dilated time interval, <strong>Δt</strong> is the proper time interval, 
            <strong>v</strong> is the relative velocity, <strong>m</strong> is the mass, and <strong>ρ</strong> is the mass 
            density. This formula suggests that both velocity and mass density contribute to time dilation, meaning 
            that denser objects experience a slower passage of time relative to less dense objects.
        </p>

        <!-- Simplified Explanation -->
        <h2><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Simplified Explanation</h2>
        <p>
            Think of time like a video you're watching. Normally, the video plays at regular speed. But if you slow the video down, everything moves in slow motion. In real life, time dilation is like hitting the slow-motion button in specific areas, like near a massive object or when something is moving really fast. The more massive the object, the slower time moves around it—just like how increasing the slow-motion effect makes everything move more slowly.
        </p>
        
